 Plaintiffs also state no claim HN8[
] under 42 U.S.C. § 1985 because that statute requires "some racial, or perhaps otherwise class-based, invidiously discriminatory animus behind the conspirators' action." Griffin v. Breckenridge, 403 U.S. 88, 102, 29 L. 
Ed. 2d 338, 91 S. Ct. 1790 (1971); Collyer v. Darling, 98 F.3d 211, 223 (6th Cir. 1996), cert. denied, 520 U.S. 1267, 138 L. Ed. 
2d 199, 117 S. Ct. 2439 (1997). Similarly, HN9[
] because Plaintiffs fail to allege that they are members of a racial minority, Plaintiffs fail to state a claim under 42 U.S.C. § 1981, which addresses racial discrimination in contractual relationships. See, 
e.g.,  Morris v. Office Max, Inc., 89 F.3d 411, 413 (7th Cir. 1996).

 HN16[
] This Court must review Plaintiff's Equal Protection claim under a rational basis standard because it fails to implicate a 
fundamental right or a suspect classification. See  Borman's v. Michigan Prop. & Cas. Guar. Ass'n., 925 F.2d 160, 162 (6th Cir.), 
cert. denied, 502 U.S. 823, 116 L. Ed. 2d 58, 112 S. Ct. 85 (1991). To prove an Equal Protection violation, Plaintiffs must allege 
an invidious discriminatory purpose or intent. See  Washington v. Davis, 426 U.S. 229, 48 L. Ed. 2d 597, 96 S. Ct. 2040 (1976); 
Massachusetts v. Feeny, 442 U.S. 256, 60 L. Ed. 2d 870, 99 S. Ct. 2282 (1979).

